{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17538939","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17538939"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T17:34:46+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T17:34:46+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16419"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16419","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16419"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.02,0.56,0.35,0.05,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9110"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111579"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9110","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9110"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16419"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93674"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1758"},{"type":"tags","id":"2436"},{"type":"tags","id":"2474"},{"type":"tags","id":"2701"},{"type":"tags","id":"3549"},{"type":"tags","id":"4982"},{"type":"tags","id":"8118"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21635"},{"type":"contributions","id":"41834"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43632"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44434"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111579","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/111579"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 68-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a six-month history of productive cough, fatigue, and unintentional weight loss of 5 kg. She has a history of bronchiectasis and previous smoking (40 pack-years). Her medications include salbutamol and tiotropium inhalers. She has no known tuberculosis contacts and lives in a low tuberculosis prevalence area. She lives alone and tends to her garden daily.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears thin. Her pulse rate is 88/min, blood pressure 125/75 mmHg, respiratory rate 20/min, SpO2 94% on room air, and temperature 37.2\u00b0C. Chest examination reveals scattered crackles and wheeze. A chest X-ray shows bilateral bronchiectasis with nodular infiltrates. Three sputum samples show acid-fast bacilli on microscopy.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Lung cancer","Non-tuberculous mycobacterial infection","Pulmonary tuberculosis","Allergic bronchopulmonary aspergillosis","Listeria pneumonia"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with chronic respiratory symptoms and constitutional symptoms in the context of pre-existing bronchiectasis. The finding of acid-fast bacilli on sputum microscopy, along with characteristic radiological findings of nodular bronchiectasis, strongly suggests mycobacterial infection. Both tuberculosis and non-tuberculous mycobacterial infection are possible given the clinical presentation. While the chronic course and underlying bronchiectasis are commonly seen with non-tuberculous mycobacterial infection, definitive diagnosis requires culture and molecular identification. However, the chronic six-month course, pre-existing bronchiectasis, lack of tuberculosis contacts, and residence in a low tuberculosis prevalence area make \u003Cstrong\u003Enon-tuberculous mycobacterial infection\u003C/strong\u003E most likely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPulmonary tuberculosis\u003C/strong\u003E remains possible given the acid-fast bacilli on microscopy. However, the epidemiological factors (no known contacts, low prevalence area), chronic indolent course, and pre-existing bronchiectasis are more typical of non-tuberculous mycobacterial infection. Culture results would be needed to definitively distinguish between the two.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EListeria pneumonia\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents more acutely with fever and systemic symptoms. \u003Cem\u003EListeria monocytogenes\u003C/em\u003E is a gram-positive, facultatively anaerobic bacillus that appears as small, round-ended rods on microscopy. Unlike mycobacteria, it does not stain with acid-fast stains, making this diagnosis highly unlikely given the microscopy findings.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELung cancer\u003C/strong\u003E could present with similar symptoms of weight loss and chronic cough, but the presence of acid-fast bacilli and bilateral bronchiectasis make mycobacterial infection more likely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAllergic bronchopulmonary aspergillosis\u003C/strong\u003E can cause bronchiectasis but typically presents with more prominent allergic symptoms and elevated IgE levels. The finding of acid-fast bacilli makes this diagnosis less likely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ENon-tuberculous mycobacteria are environmental organisms found naturally in soil and water systems, including household plumbing. The most common organism causing disease is \u003Cem\u003EMycobacterium avium\u003C/em\u003E \u003Cem\u003Ecomplex\u003C/em\u003E (MAC). Risk factors include underlying lung disease (particularly bronchiectasis), female gender, older age, and slender body habitus. The diagnosis requires compatible symptoms, characteristic radiological findings, and microbiological confirmation. Treatment typically involves a prolonged course of multiple antibiotics.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Non-tuberculous mycobacterial lung disease typically presents with chronic cough and constitutional symptoms in patients with underlying lung disease.","Bronchiectasis and nodular changes on chest imaging are characteristic of non-tuberculous mycobacterial infection.","Mycobacterium avium complex is the most common causative organism in non-tuberculous mycobacterial lung disease."],"references":["Busatto C, Vianna JS, da Silva Junior LV, Ramis IB, da Silva PE. Mycobacterium avium: an overview. Tuberculosis. 2019 Jan 1;114:127-34. Available at: https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/abs/pii/S1472979218302440","To K, Cao R, Yegiazaryan A, Owens J, Venketaraman V. General overview of nontuberculous mycobacteria opportunistic pathogens: Mycobacterium avium and Mycobacterium abscessus. Journal of clinical medicine. 2020 Aug 6;9(8):2541. Available at: https://www.mdpi.com/2077-0383/9/8/2541"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93674"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16419"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93674","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/93674"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-08-17T09:16:39+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-08-17T09:17:48+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9110"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111579"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"11","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec1","name":"Respiratory Medicine","synonyms":["Pulmonology"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"14","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/14"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udda0","name":"Infectious Diseases","synonyms":["ID"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:51:58+09:30"}